Red Wine Analysis by Kalpana

About the dataset:

The following analysis is based on the dataset by P. Cortez, A. Cerdeira, F. Almeida, T. Matos and J. Reis. Modeling wine preferences by data mining from physicochemical properties. In Decision Support Systems, Elsevier, 47(4):547-553. ISSN: 0167-9236.

Available at: [@Elsevier] http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.dss.2009.05.016 [Pre-press (pdf)] http://www3.dsi.uminho.pt/pcortez/winequality09.pdf [bib] http://www3.dsi.uminho.pt/pcortez/dss09.bib

You can read more on this from this text: https://s3.amazonaws.com/udacity-hosted-downloads/ud651/wineQualityInfo.txt

Data Wrangling:

It seems that x is an index variable which we wouldn’t need for analysis. So we can remove it. Also, the quality variable is numeric, we can convert it to factor variable.

wine <-  wine[2:13]
wine$quality <- factor(wine$quality, ordered = TRUE)
levels(wine$quality)
## [1] "3" "4" "5" "6" "7" "8"

RESIDUAL SUGAR AND CHLORIDES :

The residual sugar is the amount of sugar remaining after fermentation stops. It’s rare to find wines with less than 1 gram/liter and wines with greater than 45 grams/liter are considered sweet. The wines in our dataset have maximum 15% residual sugar ,which means they are not sweet.

ggplot(aes(x=residual.sugar), data=wine) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth=0.05, fill='blue', colour='black') + 
  scale_x_continuous(breaks=0:16)

# This is has too many outliers. lets exclude the 95th percentile

ggplot(aes(x = chlorides), data = wine) + 
  geom_histogram(fill = 'yellow3', colour = 'black')

Plotting the histogram of residual sugar and chlorides, we see many outliers. Excluded the 95th percentile and plotted again. I added a log scale to get a normalized distribution.

ggplot(wine, aes(x=residual.sugar)) + 
  geom_histogram(fill='blue', colour='black') +
  scale_x_log10(breaks=seq(1,6,1)) +
  xlim(0, quantile(wine$residual.sugar, c(0.95)))   

summary(wine$residual.sugar)

These variables have negative correlation with quality:

*volatile.acidity:quality = -0.39

*total.sulfur.dioxide:quality = -0.19

*density:quality = -0.17

*chlorides:quality = -0.13

Note the highest negative correlation is with volatile acidity. All acids in wine are non- volatile except for acetic acid which is volatile. volatile acidity is the amount of acetic acid in wine, which at too high of levels can lead to an unpleasant, vinegar taste.

Looking at the correlation between other variables, we note :

*fixed.acidity:citric.acid = 0.67

*fixed.acidity:density = 0.67

*fixed.acidity:pH = -0.68

*free.sulfur.dioxide:total.sulfur.dioxide = 0.67

*density:alcohol = -0.50

*citric.acid:pH = -0.54

pH describes how acidic or basic a wine is on a scale from 0 (very acidic) to 14 (very basic). Thus when citric acid increases, pH decreases indicating that the wine is getting more acidic. Fixed acidity includes acidity of citric acid also, as it is a non volatile acid. Obviously citric acid and fixed acidity are positively correlated. Thus pH decreases with increase in fixed acidity.

On Plotting the relationship between fixed acidity and other variables, we can understand the pattern in detail.

Fixed acidity is positively correlated with density and citric acid . Both fixed acidity and citric acid have inverse relationship with pH.

Similarly, total sulfur dioxide is the amount of free and bound forms of S02. Hence, when free sulfur dioxide increases, total sulfur dioxide also increases.

One other important relationship to note is the negative correlation of density and alcohol.

Multivariate Plots Section

The main factors which determine the quality are alcohol and sulphates. Lets plot them to see their relationships.

In the above plot, higher quality wines are at the top right and lower quality wines are at the bottom left. Though we can plot various variables against quality, Let us categorise the quality ratings so as to get a more clear picture. The quality ratings are from 3 to 8.

Let us categorise them as low, average, good and high quality wines based on the rating.

wine <- mutate(wine, rating = 
                 ifelse(quality < 5, 'Low', 
                   ifelse(quality == 5 , 'Average', 
                   ifelse(quality == 6 , 'Good', 'High'))))
wine$rating <- factor(wine$rating, 
                             levels=c("Low", "Average", "Good", "High"))

summary(wine$rating)
##     Low Average    Good    High 
##      63     681     638     217

Now let us replot the earlier plot with rating variable.

High quality wines have more alcohol and less sulphates. In average and good quality wines, the percentage of alcohol and sulphates is kind of balanced. In low quality wines, both are equally high.

Plotting density and alcohol

With increase in percentage of alcohol, density decreases. High quality wines have higher percentage of alcohol in them, but may be with a fine balance with the density.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

Citric acid has a nice positive correlation with quality(0.23). So I plotted it understand it better. To my surprise, very very small quantity (< 1 g) of citric acid was added to wine. Many wines didnot have citric acid at all (0 g/ltr). I thought it was because of inadequate data. Deeper analysis revealed there are many wines which doesnt have citric acid in it (according to tests conducted by the Food Standards Australia New Zealand website). The data and the analysis of our dataset reveals the same result.

Plot Two

Description Two

The main factors which determine the quality of the wine have been plotted. Percentage of alcohol, fixed acidity and sulphates have positive effect on quality. Wine quality and volatile acidity are negatively correlated. In all cases, we see outliers in quality ratings 5 and 6 , showing there may be other factors that influence quality.

Plot Three

Description Three

The two strong positively correlated(alcohol) and negatively correlated(volatile. acidity) factors have been plotted against quality. It is understood that high alcohol and low volatile acidity might give higher quality wines. Please note that volatile acid , acetic acid can contribute to wine fault , which might make the wine undrinkable.

Reflection

This red wine dataset has 1599 observations and 13 variables.This is a perfectly tidy and small dataset to be used for EDA by beginners.The step-by- step approach from univariate to bivariate and then to multivariate plots was a nice way to explore a dataset. It is clear from the outset , the main factors that determine the quality. but plotting the correlations revealed more insights.I guessed alcohol would be one of the main contributor. Surprisingly, sulphates and acetic acid do have roles to play. Citric acid, though correlated well, was added in very less quantities and doesnot have much effect except for the freshness in wines.

Future work would be to build a model to predict the wine quality. This dataset had more wines with rating 5 and 6. May be the next step would be to get more data on wines with other quality ratings too.

The main struggle I faced was finding an apt dataset and tidying it. I was initially browsing thro various data and chose a few. Looking in detail, there were many NAs, repetitions and a whole big bunch of data, which I did not know how to interpret. As it was taking way too much of time, I resented to one of the suggested datasets. It was worth a decision. I was able to learn a lot from this red wine dataset. Had I taken some other big dataset, I would have focussed on tidying rather than exploring the dataset.
